/*******************************************************************************
	GML rules, filters and paths
*******************************************************************************/
You can think of a rule as discussed below as a path (essentially a filter)
with an associated jit method that gets applied only when the filter matches.

There is no such concept in xml. The idea is borrowed from plg, except where
plg parses text into tokens (PLGitem), gml deals with blocks (GroupItem) and
attributes
	rule is an attribute that has an action to treat the block it occurs
	in as a rule. In the GUI it works in association with a source. In ParseXML
	may have it work in association with a path.
	
	The idea is when you check the rule it acts as a filter, matching its
	attributes against whatever you check it against. If the filter passes
	and the rule has members, each member is checked in sequence until one
	is found that matches, in which case its action is applied against the
	matching block resulting in a block that is returned from the rule as
	success. If there are no matching members the rule fails.
	
	The action of a matching rule member can modify the matched block or
	add the matched block to some other block or whatever.
	
	In essence, a rule acts like a path specification but where a path only
	does one thing, adds a matching block to the path list, a rule can do
	anything since it has the JIT at its disposal.
	
	How does a rule work in conjunction with a source and next?
	
	Can you use a rule to change how a template works or to modify gml mid-parse
	for example, to change a display depending on what is being displayed?

